<TITLE> UK`s Darling to make N Rock statement Monday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SHANGHAI, Jan 19 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - British finance minister Alistair Darling will make a statement to parliament on Monday on the troubled Northern Rock bank. The BBC's website reported Prime Minister Gordon Brown had backed a plan to convert billions of pounds of Bank of England loans to Northern Rock into bonds that would be sold to investors once credit markets stabilised. Government officials travelling with Brown in China declined to confirm the content of the report. "I can confirm that discussions are taking place with private firms that have expressed an interest," Brown said on Saturday. "I can also confirm that the chancellor (Darling) will make a statement to the House of Commons on Monday on these issues. "All options including public ownership on the road to moving the firm back into the private sector, are on the table." The bank has borrowed about 24 billion pounds ($47 billion) from Britain's central bank since a crisis erupted four months ago when it was unable to fund its business in financial markets following a credit crunch. Northern Rock and the government have said they would prefer a private sector solution to nationalisation. Talks with two potential suitors have stumbled and the bank has talked of a self-help or standalone solution. The BBC said that if the loan conversion plan was agreed, this would make it far easier to agree a deal with a Virgin consortium or with Olivan
